{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-help-account-locked-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">&ldquo;Account locked,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A locked account means Intuit &mdash; the company that owns QuickBooks &mdash; has temporarily restricted access to your Intuit account, the single login that gets you into QuickBooks Online, your subscription, and billing. Locks are a security measure: Intuit puts one in place after too many failed sign-in attempts, when something trips a fraud or security flag, or when it needs you to verify your identity before letting you back in. While the lock is on, you can&rsquo;t sign in &mdash; correct password or not.</p>
      <p>Here&rsquo;s the honest part most pages won&rsquo;t say plainly: <strong>only Intuit can unlock the account.</strong> An independent ProAdvisor firm has no access to your Intuit account, your password, or Intuit&rsquo;s security systems &mdash; we cannot unlock it for you, and anyone outside Intuit who claims they can should be treated with suspicion. The legitimate route is Intuit&rsquo;s own account-recovery flow and identity verification, covered below. What an independent firm <em>can</em> do is the part that begins once you&rsquo;re back in: the books that drifted while you were locked out.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

